question.explanation:
Rates of work:
\[
A: \frac{1}{573},\quad B: \frac{1}{382},\quad C: \frac{1}{1146}
\]

Note that \(1146 = 2 \times 573\), so:
\[
\frac{1}{573} + \frac{1}{1146}
= \frac{2}{1146} + \frac{1}{1146}
= \frac{3}{1146}
= \frac{1}{382}
\]

Therefore total rate:
\[
\frac{1}{573} + \frac{1}{382} + \frac{1}{1146}
= \frac{1}{382} + \frac{1}{382}
= \frac{2}{382}
= \frac{1}{191}
\]

So together they take \(191\) days.

Let the total work be \(W\).

Time taken by \(B = 603\) days \(\Rightarrow\) rate of \(B = \dfrac{W}{603}\).

“A works twice as fast” \(\Rightarrow\) rate of \(A = 2 \times \dfrac{W}{603} = \dfrac{2W}{603}\).

Combined rate:
\[
\dfrac{W}{603} + \dfrac{2W}{603}
= \dfrac{3W}{603}
= \dfrac{W}{201}
\]

So together they finish the work in \(201\) days.

Total work (in girl-days):
\[
18 \times 450
\]

Rate of 1 girl:
\[
\frac{1}{18 \times 450}
\]

A boy is twice as efficient as a girl, so:
\[
\text{Rate of 1 boy} = \frac{2}{18 \times 450} = \frac{1}{9 \times 450}
\]

Rate of 5 girls \(+ 2\) boys:
\[
5 \times \frac{1}{18 \times 450} + 2 \times \frac{1}{9 \times 450}
= \frac{5}{8100} + \frac{2}{4050}
= \frac{5}{8100} + \frac{4}{8100} 
= \frac{9}{8100} 
= \frac{1}{900}
\]

So they take **900 days**.

\[
\text{Speed} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}} = \frac{1620}{60} = 27\ \text{kmph}
\]
